{
  "texts": [
    "Dense models, in contrast, are easier to train and provide more robust, uniform performance, albeit at a higher computational cost during inference.The consistent accuracy, reliability, and robust performance of dense models make them the ideal choice for fine-tuning on PyChrono-related tasks.",
    "The simplicity of training dense models and their superior generalization across tasks further support their selection over MoE-based alternatives.",
    "Considering these trade-offs, we selected dense models.",
    "The chosen dense models were evaluated based on their performance in widely recognized benchmarks, such as the HumanEval benchmark for coding tasks [79] and the MMLU benchmark for general reasoning tasks [80].",
    "Specifically, in this contribution we adopt the following dense LLMs:-GPT-4o and its lightweight variant GPT-4o mini, for their good coding performance and general good knowledge about Project Chrono, -LLama3.1-8B, LLaMA3.3-70B and Llama-4-Scout-17B-16E, which are open-sourced models from 8B to 109B that offer good performance on diverse tasks,The decision to exclude certain dense models, such as CodeLLaMA [59] and StarCoder [81], is based on their limitations in our context."
  ]
}